[2] Pennsylvania (Delaware County)
Date: Fri 10 Apr 2015
Source: Delaware County Daily Times [edited]
http://www.delcotimes.com/general-news/20150410/eight-cases-of-whooping-cough-confirmed-at-radnor-high-school


Parents in the Radnor Township School District are on the lookout for whooping cough symptoms in the wake of 8 confirmed cases at 2 schools. "There have now been a total of 7 confirmed cases of pertussis at Radnor High School since [20 Mar 2015], in addition to one confirmed case at Radnor Middle School," the district said in Friday [10 Apr 2015] statement.

According to school officials, 6 of the 7 high school students stricken with the highly contagious respiratory disease had been vaccinated, "Out of the entire Radnor High School student body, 7 students are currently exempt from vaccinations for medical or religious reasons," the statement said. "Radnor High School's nurse has called the parents of all of these students in order to discuss the importance of vaccination. Ultimately it's going to be their choice," said district spokesman Michael Petitti.

Before pertussis vaccines became widely available in the 1940s, about 200 000 children got sick with it each year in the USA and about 9000 died as a result of the infection, according to the CDC website. Today, roughly 10 000 to 40 000 cases are reported each year that result in 10 to 20 deaths.

Though there is no federal requirement, all 50 states have laws requiring certain vaccines for students, according to data compiled by the National Conference of State Legislatures through 3 Mar 2015. Every state except West Virginia and Mississippi grants religious exemptions for people who do not believe in immunizations, and 20 states, including Pennsylvania, allow philosophical exemptions for objections on personal, moral, or other grounds.

Unofficial figures from the Pennsylvania Department of Health have Delaware County ranked 5th, behind Philadelphia, Allegheny, Bucks, and Montgomery counties, with 102 confirmed pertussis cases since 2013. The numbers from the state did not appear to account for the Radnor cases. Unlike Bucks, Chester, and Montgomery counties, Delaware County does not have its own health department.

[Byline: Tim Logue]

